[[File: GOC Woburn 029 Père David's Deer (Elaphurus davidianus), Woburn Deer Park (22540801604).jpg |thumb|{{lang|zh|鹿}}]]

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{liushu|p}} – a deer. Current form is highly abstracted – legs have transformed to {{zh-l|*比}} – note grouping of front and rear legs, which are bent – head has transformed to middle component (similar to {{zh-l|*凸}}/{{zh-l|*曲}}), while antlers on top and extended lip/mouth on left transformed into {{zh-l|*广}}. This transformation occurred during seal characters.

Contrast the very different development of {{zh-l|*馬|horse}}, and the transformation in {{zh-l|*廌}} (as in {{zh-l|*薦}}), which has the head of {{lang|zh|鹿}} but the legs of {{lang|zh|馬}} ({{zh-l|*灬}}).

===Etymology===
{{unc|zh}}, though possibly {{der|zh|sit|-}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). Compare {{w|Konyak languages|Northern Naga}} {{m|und|*gjuk||deer, sambar}}, from {{cog|tbq-pro|*g-rjuk}} ({{zh-ref|French, 1983}}); also according to French, Benedict relates the Tibeto-Burman item to {{cog|gvr|tr=gju|t=sheep}}, but this Gurung item may instead be related to {{cog|sit-pro|*luk||sheep}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

Within Chinese, {{zh-ref|Sagart (1999)}} relates this to {{och-l|角|horn|id=1}}.

{{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart (2014; 2020)}} compares this to Langjia {{cog|qfa-buy}} {{IPAchar|/ma⁰ lɔk⁸/}}. Note also {{cog|nut|klook||deer}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

